==Latin alphabet==
{{Main|History of the Latin alphabet}}
[[Image:Duenos inscription.jpg|thumb|[[Duenos inscription]], 6th century BC]]
21 of the 26 archaic Etruscan letters were adopted for [[Old Latin]] from the 7th century BC, either directly from the [[Cumae alphabet]], or via archaic Etruscan forms, compared to the classical Etruscan alphabet retaining B, D, K, O, Q, X but dropping Î˜, Åš, Î¦, Î¨, and F. (Etruscan U is Latin V; Etruscan V is Latin F.)
