The '''Samaritan vocalization''' (or '''Samaritan pointing''', '''Samaritan [[niqqud]]''', Hebrew: ''× ×™×§×•×“ ×©×•××¨×•× ×™'') is a system of diacritics devised by the [[Samaritans]] to add to the consonantal text of the [[Samaritan Pentateuch]] and to Samaritan prayer books to indicate vowel quality, reflecting [[Samaritan Hebrew]]. It is estimated that the Samaritan vocalization was invented around the 10th century&nbsp;CE. Only the most important vowels were indicated, and variation exists within the system between different manuscripts.

